      "category": "OWASP Top 10",
      "question": "How does Broken Access Control manifest in modern Single Page Applications (SPAs) compared to traditional server-rendered applications?",
      "answer": "In traditional server-rendered applications, access control checks are strictly enforced on the server before rendering the page, meaning unauthorized UI elements and data are never sent to the client. In contrast, SPAs often rely on client-side routing and rendering. If access control is only implemented by hiding UI elements (like admin buttons) via JavaScript rather than enforcing API-level authorization on the backend, an attacker can simply modify the client state or directly query the backend REST/GraphQL APIs. Therefore, SPAs require strict 'zero-trust' API enforcement, where every single data request and mutation is independently validated for permissions on the server, regardless of the client-side UI state."
