      "category": "Cloud Security",
      "question": "Explain the concept of an SSRF (Server-Side Request Forgery) attack specifically targeting the AWS IMDSv1. How does IMDSv2 mitigate this?",
      "answer": "An SSRF attack occurs when a vulnerable application can be tricked into making HTTP requests to arbitrary domains on an attacker's behalf. In an AWS environment using EC2, attackers commonly target the Instance Metadata Service (IMDS) at `169.254.169.254` to steal temporary IAM credentials attached to the instance role. With IMDSv1, a simple `GET /latest/meta-data/` request is sufficient to retrieve these credentials. IMDSv2 mitigates this by enforcing a session-oriented approach: it requires a `PUT` request containing a specific header (`X-aws-ec2-metadata-token-ttl-seconds`) to retrieve a temporal token, which must then be included as another header (`X-aws-ec2-metadata-token`) in subsequent `GET` requests. Since traditional SSRF vulnerabilities rarely allow attackers to send a generic `PUT` request followed by a custom-header `GET` request, IMDSv2 effectively neutralizes most cloud-based SSRF credential theft."
